document.title: Tennessee Academic Standards: Mathematics K-4th Year

425AFA74E15A4C1E9135A27AE9B4239E.description: Use a regression equation, modeling bivariate data, to make predictions. Identify possible considerations regarding the accuracy of predictions when interpolating or extrapolating.

25D50A7097DD4BE0ACA49F94228ADE53.description: Determine a regression equation to model a set of bivariate data. Justify why this equation best fits the data.

9EFD5D7719D94EEA868D2853411713AC.description: Create scatter plots, analyze patterns, and describe relationships for bivariate data (linear, polynomial, trigonometric, or exponential) to model real-world phenomena and to make predictions.

5A76CE7D808545CC9149887106CD4788.description: Represent situations and solve problems involving polar coordinates.

6BB862C717E44C32B60B43CEEF478859.description: Convert between rectangular and polar coordinates.

0CA496DE4B77407BB4BA331ED45E2B00.description: Prove the addition and subtraction formulas for sine, cosine, and tangent and use them to solve problems.

DD7DC58EA5C04B0E9705C8EC2F43AF72.description: Apply trigonometric identities to verify identities and solve equations. Identities include: Pythagorean, reciprocal, quotient, sum/difference, double-angle, and half-angle.

9A36F4AF102D43F387E8A3C6E77E9EF0.description: Apply trigonometric identities to rewrite expressions and solve equations.

BD0B9F17809D46B98F8EF9D0CD12FA6E.description: Understand and apply the Law of Sines (including the ambiguous case) and the Law of Cosines to find unknown measurements in right and non-right triangles (such as surveying problems and resultant forces).

9FCCE6C7054E4EB397FDB2C4529A5F7D.description: Prove the Laws of Sines and Cosines and use them to solve problems.

381DC368422346FA88F309880FA3172B.description: Calculate the arc length of a circle subtended by a central angle.

3AC5816990674D29BA56CFF8E3CB1C80.description: Derive and apply the formulas for the area of sector of a circle.

591D5C480D2D423980CD4822E55DD30C.description: Derive the formula A = ½ ab sin(C) for the area of a triangle by drawing an auxiliary line from a vertex perpendicular to the opposite side.

41B3112313E24537B9318FD64D56EA0E.description: Use the definitions of the six trigonometric ratios as ratios of sides in a right triangle to solve problems about lengths of sides and measures of angles.

DEA99AD5F4CD45B599B8FCCB456F2DBC.description: Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate the solutions using technology and interpret them in terms of the context.

1A511BEBBC9343FDA9069FC8D878C665.description: Graph the inverse trigonometric functions and identify their key characteristics.

8B5FB0F77B024B63AA450F3E202CF300.description: Determine the appropriate domain and corresponding range for each of the inverse trigonometric functions.

0BA43D4624B046E595764115A29F440F.description: Understand that restricting a trigonometric function to a domain on which it is always increasing or always decreasing allows its inverse to be constructed.

7BA8C93F875E421F95365FFE97738F6D.description: Find values of inverse trigonometric expressions (including compositions), applying appropriate domain and range restrictions.

56D05F08C4B84F4388835C0BE003C245.description: Graph the six trigonometric functions and identify characteristics such as period, amplitude, phase shift, and asymptotes.

4A09B0CE54034E939DED19E4EE4A6C68.description: Determine the difference made by choice of units for angle measurement when graphing a trigonometric function.

8111BB93922B4DDDB5B68C409BCDED0F.description: Model periodic phenomena with trigonometric functions.

04F354BEC5B54D359682B7C20B8A9A0F.description: Choose trigonometric functions to model periodic phenomena with specified amplitude, frequency, and midline.

171FC6588B544B579D46900B7C5D0DAF.description: Use the unit circle to explain symmetry (odd and even) and periodicity of trigonometric functions.

AD42F143C0E94870B0D06E9E925C3844.description: Use special triangles to determine geometrically the values of sine, cosine, tangent for π/3, π/4 and π/6, and explain how to use the unit circle to express the values of sine, cosine, and tangent for π–x, π+x, and 2π–x in terms of their values for x, where x is any real number.

1117C3D57DEA4B12A63C7CF021C0AEB6.description: Convert from radians to degrees and from degrees to radians.

77A17765A66A4A48A3C38EFC1105F304.description: Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.

AC2C1248D7A840EE8F144F3D3DBE2D73.description: Extend the domain of trigonometric functions using the unit circle.

9407C77F7FCD43269C35CDE1389AADF3.description: Recognize that sequences are functions, sometimes defined recursively, whose domain is a subset of the integers (for example, the Fibonacci sequence is defined recursively by f(0) = f(1) = 1, f(n + 1) = f(n) + f(n - 1) for n ≥ 1).

F6D59D520170481A8D864A7F62F63640.description: Graph rational functions, identifying zeros, asymptotes (including slant), and holes (when suitable factorizations are available) and showing end behavior.

F85789DF292144E7842ABA843876DA23.description: Visually locate critical points on the graphs of functions and determine if each critical point is a minimum, a maximum, or point of inflection. Describe intervals where the function is increasing or decreasing and where different types of concavity occur.

74A6BF65D54847D8811679E93B77F6F2.description: Identify characteristics of graphs based on a set of conditions or on a general equation such as y = ax² + c.

87F4A00971744F79B3C0E87082060FFA.description: Identify the real zeros of a function and explain the relationship between the real zeros and the x-intercepts of the graph of a function (exponential, polynomial, logarithmic, trigonometric, and rational).

F9E4F70B80A54DAA81060F74EBF9ED98.description: Analyze qualities of exponential, polynomial, logarithmic, trigonometric, and rational functions and solve real-world problems that can be modeled with these functions (by hand and with appropriate technology).

EF24741E642D4800BCE8BC42E8F8FF04.description: Determine whether a function is even, odd, or neither.

BAFC298F372A4224B37657F53F1FC6F0.description: Explain why the graph of a function and its inverse are reflections of one another over the line y = x.

290EFD481CD449F7B522755A767F42BA.description: Recognize a function is invertible if and only if it is one-to-one. Produce an invertible function from a non-invertible function by restricting the domain.

8F04968A84FB46D6A885F0BCF8D2309B.description: Read values of an inverse function from a graph or a table, given that the function has an inverse.

C82D2AB6D7614DADBF62727FBA6E6A59.description: Verify by composition that one function is the inverse of another.

058F485A18264F7EAC78E862CF54A3C2.description: Calculate the inverse of a function, f (x), with respect to each of the functional operations; in other words, the additive inverse, − f (x), the multiplicative inverse, 1/f(x), and the inverse with respect to composition, f <sup>−1</sup>(x). Understand the algebraic and graphical implications of each type.

61B3DB4DB5CA4DDFA41C9CDE3CE9FB0A.description: Find inverse functions (including exponential, logarithmic, and trigonometric).

0379F3BE56C54A86AAB522447A462785.description: Construct the difference quotient for a given function and simplify the resulting expression.

7A3E84A462814A09A32DBA883393F51E.description: Compose functions (for example, if T(y) is the temperature in the atmosphere as a function of height, and h(t) is the height of a weather balloon as a function of time, then T(h(t)) is the temperature at the location of the weather balloon as a function of time).

FAF9D13B206F4D0ABDEE49DFF7A18C96.description: Develop an understanding of functions as elements that can be operated upon to get new functions: addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and composition of functions.

FE215B9C188A4B309635ABC48965AAC1.description: Understand how the algebraic properties of an equation transform the geometric properties of its graph (for example, given a function, describe the transformation of the graph resulting from the manipulation of the algebraic properties of the equation such as translations, stretches, reflections, and changes in periodicity and amplitude).

F137366977164D219F154A4EB451FD96.description: Build new functions from existing functions.

6146F20DDEA04F39BA10DE7F76E693F8.description: Transform equations of conic sections to convert between general and standard form.

7DE11A1F83C74ED98723BC239730EF4F.description: From an equation in standard form, graph the appropriate conic section: ellipses, hyperbolas, circles, and parabolas. Demonstrate an understanding of the relationship between their standard algebraic form and the graphical characteristics.

462A8BD43CEE44C3ABE6DD2CD03C928B.description: Derive the equations of ellipses and hyperbolas given the foci, using the fact that the sum or difference of distances from the foci is constant.

E24A7457B9EE4630BA9E51772B01C886.description: Know and write the equation of a circle of given center and radius using the Pythagorean Theorem.

5471E7DC142A4189869B2E256CE36F34.description: Display all of the conic sections as portions of a cone.

1B87B09FAD6E405D89EFCAC051A10559.description: Understand the properties of conic sections and model real-world phenomena.

BFC724962D70494BB113F6001F78FB35.description: Eliminate parameters by rewriting parametric equations as a single equation.

C3B24C6030CF4B24B9449AAE8C4C00A0.description: Graph curves parametrically (by hand and with appropriate technology).

1CE6F52E653E4F27AD1A131F915B7EA8.description: Solve systems of nonlinear inequalities by graphing.

18C73DC1D1374AC1B4A6727F085C5374.description: Solve nonlinear inequalities (quadratic, trigonometric, conic, exponential, logarithmic, and rational) by graphing (solutions in interval notation if one-variable), by hand and with appropriate technology.

A42CA2427AC7456999AB19081852505E.description: Solve rational and radical equations in one variable, and identify extraneous solutions when they exist.

80B6E57B114E45D3BB79661E283FD6CD.description: Find the inverse of a matrix if it exists and use it to solve systems of linear equations (using technology for matrices of dimension 3 × 3 or greater).

3FD9D6745753400B917F7A960307F8C0.description: Represent a system of linear equations as a single matrix equation in a vector variable.

CA497F88F2B542A5824D357DA8185163.description: Solve systems of equations and nonlinear inequalities.

CE95301DF7E045BDB9FBF7130F03BE72.description: Know and apply the Binomial Theorem for the expansion of (x + y)<sup>n</sup> in powers of x and y for a positive integer n, where x and y are any numbers, with coefficients determined, for example, by Pascal's Triangle.

132A439C81FB45E4957527F825081370.description: Understand that series represent the approximation of a number when truncated; estimate truncation error in specific examples.

1FBEB2555F0649EE94D033CB3136050F.description: Find the sum of a finite arithmetic series.

2CFB98F37C674BA7962A051A2043A6AC.description: Find the sum of a given geometric series (both infinite and finite).

88AF0A25C307457294C251CED6E8FE48.description: Determine whether a given arithmetic or geometric series converges or diverges.

F3F0D408E21147A3B9025FBF46F4F8F2.description: Derive and use the formulas for the general term and summation of finite or infinite arithmetic and geometric series, if they exist.

08C4DE6E2D354C0BBC3909590060018D.description: Use sigma notation to represent a series; expand and collect expressions in both finite and infinite settings.

71D7C125DD5646A9A918529C31880429.description: Demonstrate an understanding of sequences by representing them recursively and explicitly.

4CFBC115386D408C8D353978F0641D5E.description: Understand and use sequences and series.

CCB63141384845CA9AC06316879059B9.description: Work with 2 × 2 matrices as transformations of the plane, and interpret the absolute value of the determinant in terms of area.

D182A09A77E6463F8DC1DB3B8C0CBC52.description: Multiply a vector (regarded as a matrix with one column) by a matrix of suitable dimensions to produce another vector. Work with matrices as transformations of vectors.

BCC04F94E697412FB626C92567736E95.description: Understand that the zero and identity matrices play a role in matrix addition and multiplication similar to the role of 0 and 1 in the real numbers. The determinant of a square matrix is nonzero if and only if the matrix has a multiplicative inverse.

F7D1465DFCD84467880004DCF342B719.description: Understand that, unlike multiplication of numbers, matrix multiplication for square matrices is not a commutative operation, but still satisfies the associative and distributive properties.

D5E1F62463A041AC898FC73BAF223EB4.description: Perform operations on matrices and use matrices in applications.

6C217BE59F4043ABABC6A6B104AE3040.description: Calculate and interpret the dot product of two vectors.

2BC4A76B605C4E398587E921CBA4ABA9.description: Compute the magnitude of a scalar multiple cv using ||cv|| = |c|v. Compute the direction of cv knowing that when |c|v ≠ 0, the direction of cv is either along v (for c > 0) or against v (for c < 0).

45694DFD9D494ADE8F19F6DC6098F938.description: Represent scalar multiplication graphically by scaling vectors and possibly reversing their direction; perform scalar multiplication component-wise (e.g., as c(v<sub>x</sub>, v<sub>y</sub>) = (cv<sub>x</sub>, cv<sub>y</sub>).

3C7D7096B5D848908C3AA0EE574662D5.description: Multiply a vector by a scalar.

A6C7445B0AEC4D67A93476705E643B24.description: Understand vector subtraction v – w as v + (–w), where –w is the additive inverse of w, with the same magnitude as w and pointing in the opposite direction. Represent vector subtraction graphically by connecting the tips in the appropriate order, and perform vector subtraction component-wise.

9FD117711D404392B861AA89DF024C40.description: Given two vectors in magnitude and direction form, determine the magnitude and direction of their sum.

18FA969541C54F9781721DF259ED29B9.description: Add vectors end-to-end, component-wise, and by the parallelogram rule. Understand that the magnitude of a sum of two vectors is typically not the sum of the magnitudes.

B4C964F6FA1245008C000CDA34B1C784.description: Understand the graphic representation of vectors and vector arithmetic.

B32767DF3A114AC59657F7101FA9443A.description: Solve problems involving velocity and other quantities that can be represented by vectors.

C5F60F0771E74316AA383144D0CCFD4D.description: Find the components of a vector by subtracting the coordinates of an initial point from the coordinates of a terminal point.

8BF345BAA3B04F21B8CF54E504E9A777.description: Recognize vector quantities as having both magnitude and direction. Represent vector quantities by directed line segments, and use appropriate symbols for vectors and their magnitudes (e.g., v, |v|, ||v||, .

A56A19E2494D43BF855AF6B9004A5E89.description: Represent and model with vector quantities.

05EE084A1BCA4E139322C1988891E948.description: Know the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra; show that it is true for quadratic polynomials.

593C9E8D9F314B928BED8E5E35100BBF.description: Solve quadratic equations with real coefficients that have complex solutions.

F15A28732B7F4509B12ABA7C9C1B67A1.description: Extend polynomial identities to the complex numbers (for example, rewrite x² + 4 as (x + 2i)(x – 2i).

40C34D98379D42329FCE3FA72D079D27.description: Use complex numbers in polynomial identities and equations.

AC6DE61DD2474B62B4F2A8D77D1F0F76.description: Calculate the distance between numbers in the complex plane as the modulus of the difference, and the midpoint of a segment as the average of the numbers at its endpoints.

7B392122A6A9498DB05E175881847F70.description: Represent addition, subtraction, multiplication, and conjugation of complex numbers geometrically on the complex plane; use properties of this representation for computation (for example, (–1 + 3i)³ = 8 because (–1 + 3i) has modulus 2 and argument 120°).

B3B3D586D5644BFC9E8CFED1426D7592.description: Represent complex numbers on the complex plane in rectangular and polar form (including real and imaginary numbers), and explain why the rectangular and polar forms of a given complex number represent the same number.

828F766E0F6D442AA48045E76C695A0C.description: Find the conjugate of a complex number; use conjugates to find moduli and quotients of complex numbers.

F7D4388842FA419E9864EBF119EBDF6A.description: Perform arithmetic operations with complex numbers expressing answers in the form a + bi.

8B92481D352A42C6B0C66FB0A0FA3B0E.description: Know there is a complex number i such that i² = –1, and every complex number has the form a + bi with a and b real.

3C8277C0F6544218B957D60D06395280.description: Perform complex number arithmetic and understand the representation on the complex plane.

0E383EB775D14E5D90FD01EB259F1D5A.description: Understand that rational expressions form a system analogous to the rational numbers, closed under addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division by a nonzero rational expression; add, subtract, multiply, and divide rational expressions.

990D3331A57748BBAD3132DCEB468D0F.description: Simplify complex radical and rational expressions; discuss and display understanding that rational numbers are dense in the real numbers and the integers are not.

C45AAFE0F41C413490574DB75FEA41AF.description: Classify real numbers and order real numbers that include transcendental expressions, including roots and fractions of π and e.

9C21996A75B5457D94CCAC66CA54D870.description: Understand the inverse relationship between exponents and logarithms and use this relationship to solve problems involving logarithms and exponents.

9AAED3B153C544BCBA473E239AA80F50.description: Use the laws of exponents and logarithms to expand or collect terms in expressions; simplify expressions or modify them in order to analyze them or compare them.

0DA8B4ED202544AAA8355F2E200409A7.description: Represent, interpret, compare, and simplify number expressions.
